# Woodworking Plan — environment variables
#
# Copy to .env.local for local development:
#   Copy-Item .env.example .env.local   (PowerShell)
#
# .env / .env.* are gitignored (except this file). NEVER commit real values.
# See DEPLOYMENT.md for how to obtain each of these.
#
# All three are OPTIONAL in development/test and REQUIRED in production —
# see src/env.ts. The app runs locally without them; it reports each service
# as "not configured" on the Sprint 0 status page.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Neon Postgres  (free tier — https://neon.com)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Use the POOLED connection string from the Neon dashboard (the one with
# "-pooler" in the host). Serverless functions open many short-lived
# connections; the pooled endpoint is what survives that.
#
# *** THIS MUST BE THE `dev` BRANCH, NOT `production`. ***
#
# Neon's free tier includes 10 branches. `.env.local` points at `dev`; only
# Vercel's environment variables point at `production`. That separation is the
# only thing standing between a routine `npm run db:seed` and overwriting live
# user data. `npm run db:seed` prints the target host on every run — read it.
#
# See DEPLOYMENT.md for how to create the branch.
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:password@ep-example-pooler.region.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require"

# DIRECT (non-pooled) connection to the SAME database. Note: no "-pooler".
#
# Used ONLY by `prisma migrate` / `db push`. Neon's pooled endpoint is PgBouncer
# in transaction mode and cannot do the session-level work a migration needs
# (advisory locks, shadow database, session DDL) — it fails with
# "P1017 Server has closed the connection".
#
# Get it from the same Neon "Connection Details" panel: toggle connection
# pooling OFF and copy the string. It is identical to DATABASE_URL except the
# host has no "-pooler".
DIRECT_URL="postgresql://user:password@ep-example.region.aws.neon.tech/neondb?sslmode=require"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Clerk  (free tier — https://clerk.com)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Publishable key: safe to expose to the browser by design.
NEXT_PUBLIC_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY="pk_test_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx"

# Secret key: SERVER ONLY. If this ever leaks, rotate it in the Clerk
# dashboard immediately. Never prefix it with NEXT_PUBLIC_.
CLERK_SECRET_KEY="sk_test_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Upstash Redis  (free tier — https://upstash.com)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Rate limiting for server actions. A Next.js server action is a PUBLIC HTTP
# endpoint — anyone can POST to it in a loop — and without a limiter every hit
# costs a Neon query on a free tier with a hard monthly compute budget.
#
# These are OPTIONAL. The limiter FAILS OPEN: without them, requests are simply
# allowed and a warning is logged. It is an abuse control, not an authorization
# control (authorization is requireUser(), which fails closed). An abuse control
# that takes the app down when its store is unreachable is a worse bug than the
# abuse it prevents.
#
# Get both from the Upstash console after creating a Redis database.
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL="https://xxxx-xxxxx-00000.upstash.io"
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN="AXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX"
